A DIY, Mountain goat hunt in the wilderness will separate the men from the boys! I was blessed to accompany my nephew @duckbotch & my brother @montanatreasureisland on his first ever mountain goat hunt in Montana! This was an old Billy, who damn near outsmarted us! It came down to true grit and 9500 feet in elevation gain to get within 300 yards of this magnificent creature. Brother Al drop the hammer at 300 yards with a model 48 Nosler chambered in 300 short mag, 190gr. Accubond long range found its mark and the rest was history! Huge shout out to the boys at Kenetrek for hooking us up with some amazing boots and the Kryptek boys for sending us the ultimate camouflage to blend in with the surrounding terrain!

I Waited 38 years to draw this tag and made the best of it. Yesterday we snuck up on what seemed like a small herd of elk with several bulls that deserved a closer look. After a quick dash through some rough terrain we closed the distance to find out there were over 200 elk in a big herd. My brother Al called out the big 7 and I was able to make a one- shot- kill with the .33 Nosler at 454 yards. Walking up on this magnificent creature,  in some of the most beautiful country imaginable, I realized just how blessed I was! I have meat for the table and memories that will last forever. 9.5 miles on foot is how you separate yourself from others. I am thankful I can still go hard at 55. What’s your longest pack out on foot? Leave your comments below. #blessed

Spent the day hiking well over 6 miles glassing up whitetail bucks on the move with my brother Al. Later in the morning we sat down trying to get out of the high winds coming off the East slope of the Rockies. Suddenly a beautiful buck darted across the rolling slope in hot pursuit of a doe in estrous. We quickly scrambled to grab our gear and hoofed it after the love sick buck. By the time we caught up with him he had covered a great distance. I had a pretty good shot but missed him off my knee at 250. He ran out chasing the doe not giving a hoot that a 265 grain accu-bond  wizzed by him nearly sealing the deal. He moved out to 706 yards and I dialed up 13 MOA and held 2.5MOA for the 30+ mph winds and dropped the hammer. Al said you got him brother! We watched the buck run over and disappear into the draw. Al and I set up on the draw with me going to the last place we saw him while Al staged at the bottom incase he was still on his feet. As I worked my way into position I saw the buck get up and walk a few steps. A final shot and the rest was history!
Truly blessed 🥰

We had an incredible time today on the new “Pursuit”podcast hosted by Cascade County’s Sheriff, Jesse Slaughter! I was joined by our president of Global Accountabilty Corp., my younger brother Al. We talked about our “Tap to Indentify” geofencing patent and how the exciting the future will look for law enforcement credentials. Our system is able to end imposters, provide transparency and accountability, bring customized surveys for the public to leave feedback on as well as the “built in” recruiting functions and so much more! 

We have the best solution for de escalating interactions between the public & our nation’s law enforcement agencies! So starting in 2024 you’re going to see a lot more from our “Montana based”  C Corp! 

Stay tuned for Jesse’e podcast called “Pursuit” which brings interesting people & their stories to the masses! I promise you won’t wanna miss this episode slated for Mid December. #pursuitpodcast #globalaccountabilitycorp
